'''Kigensetsu''' (紀元節) was a Japanese holiday established to commemorate the day on which, according to the ''{{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記}}'' and ''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀}}'', the first {{ill|Emperor of Japan|ja|天皇}}—{{ill|Emperor Jimmu|ja|神武天皇}}—ascended to the throne. The date was set as {{ill|February 11|ja|2月11日}} in 660 BCE. It was established in {{ill|1873|ja|1873年}} (Meiji 6). Formerly one of the four major national holidays (''Yonjōsetsu''){{efn|The four major national holidays (Yonjōsetsu) were the old system’s four primary festival days: Kigensetsu (Feb. 11), Shihōsetsu (Jan. 1), Tenchōsetsu (the Emperor’s birthday), and Meijisetsu.}} among the old national holidays.
Following the promulgation and enforcement of the {{ill|Act on National Holidays (Japan)|ja|国民の祝日に関する法律}} on July 20, 1948, Kigensetsu and the other ''Yonjōsetsu'' holidays were abolished.<ref>{{Cite journal|language=ja|author=小野雅章 |date=2021-03 |url=https://doi.org/10.20554/nihondaigakukyouikugakkai.57.0_1 |title=象徴天皇制下における祝日学校儀式の展開過程 : 復古的天皇観と象徴天皇観との相克 |journal=教育學雑誌 |ISSN=02884038 |publisher=日本大学教育学会 |volume=57 |page=1 |doi=10.20554/nihondaigakukyouikugakkai.57.0_1 |id={{CRID|1390850578954444160}}}}</ref> In {{ill|1966|ja|1966年}} (Shōwa 41), the same date of February 11 was re-established as {{ill|National Foundation Day|ja|建国記念の日}} as a public holiday, effective the following year.
The date of February 11 was determined by converting the date in the ''Nihon Shoki''—recorded as the 1st day of the 1st month of the year Jimmu ascended the throne (660 BCE)—into the Gregorian calendar during the Meiji era.
